          <text>
                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Richmond</placeName>, <date>January
                                                  22.1849</date>.</p>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Revrd. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">Respected Friend,</p>
                              <p rend="indent(5)">It seems that<lb/> you have not read my letter as
                                        I intended &amp; that I<lb/> have alarmed you unnecessarily.
                                        I did not intend to<lb/> communicate the information that ll
                                        of your Claims<lb/> here were offsetted by <persName>Jacob
                                                  Ezekiel's</persName> indebtedness<lb/> but that
                                        some were perhaps in that condition &amp; others<lb/> could
                                        not be collected from other causes inability deaths<lb/>
                                        &amp;c; and also my remarks about your matters
                                        remaining<lb/> in <persName>Ezekiel's</persName> hands, were
                                        not intended to charge him<lb/> with dishonesty, but meant
                                        that your matters could not<lb/> prosper in the hands of
                                        such an agent, who (it is<lb/> evident to me) has been very
                                        luke-warm in your interest<lb/> to say the least. I have no
                                        doubt in the hands of some<lb/> enterprising person your
                                        interests could be largely aug-<lb/>-mented, as I wrote in
                                        my previous letter. As regards<lb/> the claim you hold
                                        against me, I did not wish to use<lb/> any plea to get off,
                                        but was under the impression that<lb/>
                                        <persName>Ezekiel</persName> had given me credit for the
                                        amount and made<lb/> correct returns to you for the
                                                  <sic>ammount</sic> for I feel fully satisfied that
                                        I<lb/> have paid him for some volumes of the Occident in
                                        cash<lb/> &amp; have his receipt, but cannot put my hand on
                                        it at<lb/> this moment, notwithstanding I will pay what I
                                        owe you<lb/> as it is hard for you to loose under either circumstances,<lb/>
                                        <persName>Ezekiel</persName> owes me so much, he can owe me
                                        a little more</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>I had some conversation with <persName>Mr. Isaac
                                        Hyneman</persName><lb/> to-day, who was one of the persons
                                        referred to in my<lb/> last, who has been under the same
                                        impression as<lb/> myself as regards
                                                  <persName>Ezekiel</persName> having given him
                                        credit for the<lb/> amount, but says you shall not suffer by
                                        him &amp; that<lb/> he will pay his account excepting for
                                        the numbers, which<lb/> he did not receive, amounting to
                                        about 1 vol. In all. I will<lb/> authorize <persName>Mr. N.
                                                  Ezekiel</persName> to allow him the amount he<lb/>
                                        wishes deducted. I will on to-morrow get your matters<lb/>
                                        out of <persName>Jacob Ezekiels</persName> hands &amp; place
                                        them with your<lb/> Agent <persName>Mr. N.
                                                  Ezekiel</persName>, who I hope will make an
                                        efficient<lb/> one. The next Occidents you forward, he
                                        wishes you to<lb/> send by Adams Express Serv; direct to
                                                  <persName>N. Ezekiel</persName> care of<lb/>
                                        <persName>Jacob A Levy</persName>. I will pay over to him
                                        the money I owe<lb/> &amp; will endeavour with <persName>Mr.
                                                  N. E.</persName> to collect all I can<lb/> I have
                                        nothing of interest to communicate. Our Ball<lb/> in aid of
                                        the Hebrew School Fund takes place on the<lb/>
                                        <date>7<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Feby.</date>
                                        <persName>Mrs. Myers</persName> the eldest daughter of
                                                  <persName>Jos. Marx</persName><lb/> deceased died
                                        here on the <date>17<hi rend="sup">th</hi></date> Inst.</p>
                              <p>Hoping that you are in Health</p>
                              <p rend="indent(4)">I remain</p>
                              <p rend="indent(4)">your Friend</p>
                              <p rend="indent(4)">
                                        <persName role="author">Isaac A Levy</persName>
                              </p>
                              <p>P. S. If you should hear of a suitable person to fill the<lb/>
                                        office of Hazan, let me hear from you</p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">
                                        <placeName>371 Walnut Street</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">
                                        <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
                              </p>
